<section class="card">
  <h2>What “Last Frost Date” Means</h2>

  <p>
    Your <strong>average last frost date</strong> is a historical average — not a promise.
    It represents when freezing nights become unlikely, not impossible.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Some years frost ends earlier.</li>
    <li>Some years frost lingers.</li>
    <li>Microclimates can shift your real conditions by several days.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Use last frost as a stable reference point, then check real conditions before planting tender crops.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Zones vs Frost Dates</h2>

  <p>
    Hardiness zones describe average winter minimum temperatures. They do <strong>not</strong> tell you your last frost date.
  </p>

  <p>
    Two gardeners in the same zone can have different frost timing.
    Frost dates are the better planning tool for spring scheduling.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>How to Use the Date Correctly</h2>

  <p>
    Last frost is the anchor for three common decisions:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Indoor starts:</strong> count backward by the recommended weeks for your crop.</li>
    <li><strong>Hardening off:</strong> plan 7–10 days before moving plants outdoors.</li>
    <li><strong>Transplant timing:</strong> warm-season crops need safer nights and warmer soil than the calendar alone suggests.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    If you want the full method behind indoor timing, see
    <a href="/guides/when-to-start-seeds-indoors/">When to Start Seeds Indoors</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short-Season Note (U.S. + Canada)</h2>

  <p>
    In colder northern U.S. climates and comparable Canadian regions,
    the instinct is often to start everything earlier. The more reliable approach is to match indoor timing to realistic outdoor conditions.
  </p>

  <p>
    If soil is cold and wet, warm-season crops can stall even after frost risk declines.
    Use last frost to plan, then let nighttime temperatures and soil warmth decide the final move.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <details>
    <summary>Is the last frost date exact?</summary>
    <p>
      No. It’s an average based on historical climate data. Freezing can occur earlier or later in any given year.
    </p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Can I plant before my last frost date?</summary>
    <p>
      Sometimes for cold-tolerant crops. Warm-season crops like tomatoes and peppers should wait until frost risk is low and nights are consistently warmer.
    </p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>What if I can’t find a frost date for my exact town?</summary>
